"Sure, Captain. They should be on their way by now, they were still in the mess hall to pick up their rations." Around 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a box and began speaking.
"We will be relocated to forward deployment base I-131, fifty miles outside Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the subsequent attack on Ianlos to drive out the rebels. There, we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Fall in with your squads and mount up."
The company broke up into the respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed among the tanks by the sergeants. Cohren climbed into one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemec, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days ago but knew little about them. He sat sideways and let his legs dangle while adjusting his backpack and the radio equipment, which was connected to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?"
"Are you talking about the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they had let the animal go at a farm. "Yes, I believe it's him."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could see the movement of a small rooster, who was constantly turning its head to search its surroundings.
"Yes, he is still with him," Cohren answered as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
""All tanks advance," the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the tank and Stryker convoy roared as they started moving. The Kronos tank, in which Cohren rode, jolted as the brakes released and they fell into formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania plain. Despite the winter storms, the marshlands were frozen and the forests snow-covered, yet the mud was everywhere.
"After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. 'Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?'"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm," Cohren replied. "We thought the matter would be wrapped up in a few weeks, but we underestimated them."
"Underestimated is a gross understatement," Nemic interjected into the conversation. "We were not prepared for their arsenal and the sheer number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only defeated Erebus last month. We should even encounter them on our way."
"I stand firmly by the side of the Federation," Orson said defiantly. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You're saying that now. But I've seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you take cover as soon as they hear a shot," Craith explained.
"Time will tell," Cohren said laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Cohren XO, Cohren CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We are receiving heat signatures approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed onto the tank and put on his special goggles. When he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could make out the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," Cohren replied through his throat microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Cohren cannot confirm," replied Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, engage only under fire. Let's lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like heat signatures took shape. As they came even closer, one of them ran hastily off to get something. She immediately returned to the small hill where the others were stationed. The figures lay down on the ground, taking their shooting positions.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw called over the radio as orange tracer bullets were fired from the hill. While the tanks were under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket flew past and hit the ground behind the formation, exploding and scattering debris and rocks onto one of the tanks. Another hit a side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly got out and took cover as the ammunition went up in flames.
"Tank Zug Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 meters. Engage," shouted the commander over the radio. Tank Zug Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew towards the hill and exploded, sending mud and stone into the air.
